  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent, detect, and report money laundering activities. These obligations typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verify customer identities\n- Assess customer risk profiles\n- Monitor and report suspicious transactions\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- File Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Report large cash transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n\n3. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Programs\n- Develop comprehensive compliance programs\n- Train employees on AML regulations\n- Implement internal controls and monitoring systems\n\n4. Know Your Customer (KYC) Procedures\n- Conduct background checks\n- Verify source of funds\n- Identify potential high-risk customers\n\n5. Compliance with Regulations\n- Follow Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) requirements\n- Adhere to international AML standards\n- Cooperate with law enforcement investigations\n\n6. Risk Assessment\n- Regularly evaluate money laundering risks\n- Update risk management strategies\n- Conduct periodic internal audits\n\nFailure to comply with these obligations can result in significant legal penalties, fines, and potential criminal charges.",
